      <bioghist id="aspace_7ee15ea6973858d4889eea9c8be5c28c">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Smith Ely Jelliffe (1866-1945) was a neurologist, psychiatrist, and psychanalyst who is regarded as one of the founders of psychosomatic medicine in the United States. Jelliffe was born in Brooklyn, New York, attended Brooklyn Polytechnic Institute, completed an M.D. at College of Physicians and Surgeons, Columbia University, New York, in 1889, and earned a PhD. from Columbia University in 1899 with a thesis on the flora of Long Island. He taught materia medica and pharmacognosy at Columbia University, then became a Clinical Professor of Mental Diseases at Fordham University, New York, New York, from 1907-1912.</p>
         <p>Jelliffe was a prolific writer, editor,and translator. In 1899 he started a position as associate editor of the <title>
               <part>Journal of Nervous and Mental Diseases</part>
            </title>, then became managing editor and owner from 1902-1945. Beginning in 1907, Jelliffe, in collaboration with William A. White, published the <title>
               <part>Nervous and Mental Diseases Monograph Series</part>
            </title>, which included the earliest translations of writings by Freud, Jung, Adler, and other European psychoanalysts available in the United States. In 1913, continuing his collaboration with White, he published <title>
               <part>The Modern Treatment of Nervous and Mental Diseases</part>
            </title> (Philadelphia, Pennsylvania: Lea &amp; Febiger) and co-founded the journal <title>
               <part>Psychoanalytic Review</part>
            </title>, the first English-language publication dedicated to psychoanalysis. In 1918 Jelliffe published <title>
               <part>The Technique of Psychoanalysis</part>
            </title> (New York: Nervous and Mental Disease Publication Co.), the first book devoted to analytical technique. In 1939 he published <title>
               <part>Sketches in Psychosomatic Medicine</part>
            </title> (New York: Nervous and Mental Disease Monographs No. 65).</p>
         <p>Jelliffe was highly regarded in the United States and Europe. During his career he served as president of the New York Psychiatric Society, the New York Neurological Society, and the American Psychopathological Association and in 1928 he presided over the July 21 session of the third Conférence des Psychanalystes de Langue Française in Paris, France.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <prefercite id="aspace_8ffcfd6c2dd21ca07fa16e1c68eb722f">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>Smith Ely Jelliffe collection of New York State Psychiatric Institute lantern slides. Historical Library, Harvey Cushing / John Hay Whitney Medical Library, Yale University.</p>
      </prefercite>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_93b052ef9fac934c8bba6ba44a728e70">
         <head>Content Description</head>
         <p>The collection includes 167 lantern slides owned by neurologist, psychiatrist, and psychoanalyst  Smith Ely Jelliffe regarding the New York State Psychiatric Institute and Hospital in New York, New York. Slides include images of female and male patients, identified by name or case number; physicians; institute buildings; informational slides about mental and physical conditions; and patients' drawings and paintings. The collection also includes part of a handwritten note regarding Presbyterian Hospital.</p>
         <p>The New York State Psychiatric Institute was established in 1895 as part of Columbia University and was one of the first institutions in the United States to integrate teaching, research and therapeutic approaches to the care of patients with mental illnesses. In 1925, the Institute added general hospital facilites when it became affiliated with Presbyterian Hospital, now New York-Presbyterian Hospital.</p>
      </scopecontent>
